values:
my chest infection is completely gone now.

I had been working on an essay, but I gave myself too much time with it and have decided it's crap.

I also decided I need to re-read all my Bloom County books before I post about it.  It was too big a part of my creative development to give a half  assed shot at. 

for now, a half assed post focused on my favorite easy target, The Family Circus




First. Where did Billy find a loin cloth? I'm guessing in daddy and mommy's "Dress Up drawer".

Second. Why is mom taking time to ask Billy a stupid question, when the average mom would be half way across the lawn by now, hoping the neighbors aren't watching?



The image was taken from Tarzan in Non-Tarzan Comics so, y'know, if yer curious...

I'm currently 10 days into a pretty bad upper-respiratory infection. I'm on pills and inhalers and all that good stuff. As a result, I've only got time to write my main writing projects.

So this is on hold till I have the energy to stay up later.

See you guys soon.

Been too sick and busy to update recently. Half way through the next post, hope to have it up Monday.

In the meantime, a link to THE YELLOW KID ON THE PAPER STAGE

Yellow Kid was the first big break for newspaper comic strips. An innovative strip that helped establish comics as a mainstay in American newspapers. As far as I understand it, he was one of the first, if not the first recurring comic strip characters.

The site is pretty darn big and give you more info than you'll ever want to know, as well as many of Outcault's pre-Yellow Kid works. like this one:




HAHAHA ROFL! Lollercopters! 23 Skiddo!

Tight on Time, working on a post about Bloom County, in the meantime.

Before Keane started Family Circus, and before his son took over and before everyone found out just how much blood you can get from a corpse, Keane did these:







ok, so maybe much hasn't changed

there are more at: from http://www.familycircus.com/

found at: http://www.gocomics.com/fredbasset/



Is Fred Basset only around because it doesn't scare old people?

"Look Grandma, no chance of a heart attack if you read this!"

If you like to drink your Ensure at room temperature, this is the strip for you.

This probably isn't the best week to review Fred Basset. It happens to be one of the liveliest weeks I've seen form the strip. There is actually action and movement in a lot of the strips last week. But it's all in comparison to the static, unfunny norm that is Fred Basset.

99% of all Fred Basset jokes are, essentially, "I am a dog."

It's not badly done, it's just boring. boring. boring.

This strip does a good job of conveying movement. It does succeed in doing what it sets out to do. That's about all I can say for it. They probably create this strip with cutouts and a felt board.
